# `loading.tsx` — acceptable waiting state

## Doctrine

```txt
loading.tsx = acceptable waiting state
```

`loading.tsx` is not decoration. It defines what the user sees while the route segment streams. It is the **streaming contract** for its segment.

When placed alongside `page.tsx`, Next.js automatically wraps the page content in a `<Suspense>` boundary. The layout renders immediately as a **static shell**; the loading skeleton appears instantly; once the page component resolves, its HTML replaces the skeleton.

Docs: [Next.js streaming — loading.js](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/loading)

---

## Afenda rule

```md
Add loading.tsx when page-level async work should not block the shell.
```

Specifically: when `page.tsx` performs async data fetches and the layout shell (sidebar, topbar, nav) must appear instantly regardless of how long the query takes.

---

## What `loading.tsx` wraps (docs-validated)

`loading.tsx` automatically wraps **both `page.tsx` and `not-found.tsx`** in a Suspense boundary.

Component hierarchy within a segment:
```
layout → template → error → [loading wraps] → not-found / page
```

The layout is the static shell that is *outside* the Suspense boundary. The Suspense boundary covers everything inside.

---

## Correct use in Afenda

```txt
app/[locale]/o/[orgSlug]/dashboard/loading.tsx    ✓ dashboard page streams
app/[locale]/o/[orgSlug]/admin/loading.tsx         ✓ admin page streams
app/[locale]/operator/loading.tsx                  ✓ operator page streams
app/[locale]/o/[orgSlug]/dashboard/sale/loading.tsx ✓ per-module skeleton
```

Use it when:

- The layout shell (sidebar, topbar) can render first
- Page-level data may take time (DB query, AI response, slow API)
- Module content can stream independently
- Users should keep full navigation context during load

---

## Best Afenda pattern

```txt
layout.tsx   → renders shell immediately (Tier A data only)
loading.tsx  → renders module skeleton
page.tsx     → streams real content
```

### Example skeleton pattern

```tsx
// dashboard/loading.tsx  (URL segment — chrome is Nexus)
export { default } from "#components/nexus-route-loading"

// components/nexus-route-loading.tsx
import { SegmentRouteSpinner } from "#components/segment-route-spinner"
export default function NexusRouteLoading() {
  return <SegmentRouteSpinner />
}
```

---

## Anti-patterns

### Do not use `loading.tsx` to hide layout discipline problems

If the entire dashboard shell waits for non-critical data (e.g. org switcher, notifications, activity feed), the fix is splitting the layout into **Tier A blocking** and **Tier B streamable** — not adding `loading.tsx` to mask the delay.

```txt
WRONG: layout fetches everything → loading.tsx hides the wait
RIGHT: layout fetches Tier A only → Tier B slots stream via Suspense
```

### Do not add `loading.tsx` speculatively

Only add it when the page performs async work that benefits from an instant static shell. Trivial synchronous pages do not need a skeleton.

---

## Relationship to Tier A / Tier B split

`loading.tsx` operates at the **page layer**, not the layout layer.

The Tier A/B split happens inside `layout.tsx`:
- Tier A resolves before the shell renders → blocking `Promise.all`
- Tier B streams behind `Suspense` → individual Server Component slots

`loading.tsx` then covers the **page itself**, allowing the fully-rendered shell (including Tier B slots as they arrive) to stay visible while the page content resolves.

See `layout-contract.mdc` for the full Tier A/B doctrine.

---

## Benefits (Next.js docs)

Adding `loading.tsx` improves:

- **TTFB** — layout HTML is sent immediately
- **FCP** — skeleton appears instantly, navigation feels responsive  
- **TTI** — shared layouts stay interactive while page streams
- **Navigation interruptibility** — user can navigate away mid-load
